Invoking: `validate` with `{'patch': '--- a/ext/standard/var.c
+++ b/ext/standard/var.c
@@ -183,8 +183,8 @@ PHPAPI void php_var_dump(zval *struc, int level) /* {{{ */
 					if (!Z_ISUNDEF_P(val) || prop_info) {
 						php_object_property_dump(prop_info, val, num, key, level);
 					}
-				} ZEND_HASH_FOREACH_END();
-				zend_release_properties(myht);
+				} ZEND_HASH_FOREACH_END();
+				zend_release_properties(myht);
 			}
 			if (level > 1) {
 				php_printf("%*c", level-1, ' ');'}`
responded: Now I understand the issue! The problem is that the `ZEND_HASH_FOREACH_KEY_VAL` macro creates an iterator that holds pointers into the hash table. When `php_object_property_dump` calls `php_var_dump` recursively, and that recursive call processes another object that might share the same underlying hash table or affect the reference counting, the hash table can be freed while the iterator is still active.

The fix is to move the `zend_release_properties(myht)` call to after the `ZEND_HASH_FOREACH_END()` macro, so that the hash table is not released while we're still iterating over it.

Let me create the patch:

Invoking: `validate` with `{'patch': '--- a/ext/standard/var.c
+++ b/ext/standard/var.c
@@ -183,8 +183,8 @@ PHPAPI void php_var_dump(zval *struc, int level) /* {{{ */
 					if (!Z_ISUNDEF_P(val) || prop_info) {
 						php_object_property_dump(prop_info, val, num, key, level);
 					}
-				} ZEND_HASH_FOREACH_END();
-				zend_release_properties(myht);
+				} ZEND_HASH_FOREACH_END();
+				zend_release_properties(myht);
 			}
 			if (level > 1) {
 				php_printf("%*c", level-1, ' ');'}`
